olatility (CV = 388%)\\n   \\u2022 PJM AEP shows much lower volatility (CV = 43.5%)\\n   \\u2022 ERCOT's price range ($4,217/MWh) is 14.9x larger than PJM's ($283/MWh)\\n   \\u2022 ERCOT experienced negative prices (-$9.62/MWh) while PJM minimum was $9.33/MWh\\n\\n3. PRICE SPIKES:\\n   \\u2022 ERCOT West reached $4,207/MWh (99th percentile: $1,750/MWh)\\n   \\u2022 PJM AEP maximum was $292/MWh (99th percentile: $82/MWh)\\n   \\u2022 High price spikes in ERCOT create significant arbitrage opportunities\\n\\n4. DEGRADATION IMPACT:\\n   \\u2022 ERCOT: $1.34M degradation penalty (15% of gross revenue)\\n   \\u2022 PJM: $161K degradation penalty (50% of gross revenue)\\n   \\u2022 Higher cycling in ERCOT leads to greater degradation costs\\n\\n5. MARKET DYNAMICS:\\n   \\u2022 ERCOT's energy-only market design with scarcity pricing drives high volatility\\n   \\u2022 PJM's capacity market and regulated structure results in stable prices\\n   \\u2022 ERCOT West is optimal for energy arbitrage; PJM AEP offers limited opportunities\\n\\n==========================================================================================\\nCONCLUSION\\n==========================================================================================\\n\\nFor a 100 MW / 2-hour battery storage system in 2023:\\n\\n\\u2713 ERCOT WEST HUB is the clear winner for energy arbitrage:\\n  - Net Revenue: $8.92M/year ($89K/MW-year)\\n  - High price volatility creates abundant arbitrage opportunities\\n  - Extreme price spikes ($4,200+/MWh) drive significant revenue\\n\\n\\u2717 PJM AEP HUB offers limited arbitrage potential:\\n  - Net Revenue: $100K/year ($1K/MW-year)\\n  - Stable prices limit arbitrage opportunities\\n  - Degradation costs consume 50% of gross revenue\\n\\nRECOMMENDATION: ERCOT West Hub provides 89x higher arbitrage revenue and is\\nsignificantly more attractive for battery storage investments focused on energy\\narbitrage strategies.\\n===================================================